Limit the amount of prose text on the home page - try to use less than 30 sentences.
The first action of most users is to scan the homepage for link titles and major headings. Requiring users to read large amounts of prose text can slow them considerably, or they may avoid reading it altogether.

Options



Omitting IMG WIDTH or HEIGHT attributes means page text jumps about as images load.
This makes the page very hard to read while it's loading, and the user may click on the wrong link if it moves as it's being clicked. Add width and height attributes to the img tag matching the image dimensions. Authoring tools like Dreamweaver can automate this process.
Line 102 Usability.gov 14:3
Options


<img src="/gsnew/images/logo.png" width="275px;" alt="National Cancer Institute">

103


Ensure that foreground and background colors have enough contrast. The foreground/background contrast ratio is 3.908796. The ratio should be 3.0 or more for large text, 4.5 or more for all other text. For links this applies to both visited and unvisited styles.
Some users find it hard to read light gray text on a white background, dark gray text on a black background and white text on a red background.
Line 103 WCAG 1.0 AAA 2.2 WCAG 2.0 AA 1.4.3

Avoid specifying a new window as the target of a link with target="_blank".
Displaying new windows without warning can be very confusing to non-sighted and mobile users. Some screen readers and mobile devices give very little indication a new tab or window has opened. If you cannot avoid displaying a new window, insert a warning into the link text like the following: "opens in a new window".
Line 114 WCAG 1.0 AA 10.1 WCAG 2.0 AAA F22
Options


<a href="https://i2e-test.nci.nih.gov/workbench/WorkbenchView" target="_blank">Workbench |</a>


Headings must be nested correctly. For example, H2 must appear after H1, H3 after H2 etc.
Renumber headings so that the top level heading is H1, sub-headings are H2 and so on. Use CSS style rules to change heading font styles if needed.

Each A tag must contain text or an IMG with an ALT attribute.
Add text to the link, or ALT text if the link contains an image. If there is no link text or the ALT tag is blank, screen readers have nothing to read, so read out the URL instead.

This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 153 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)

Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.

271


Identify row and column headers in data tables using TH elements, and mark layout tables with role='presentation'.
Data tables allow screen reader users to understand column and row relationships. Layout tables read cells as a series of unrelated paragraphs with no tabular structure. Without TH or ROLE, screen readers apply heuristics to decide whether a table is a layout table or data table. These heuristics vary greatly between screen readers, and are affected by browser being used, window size, and font size (so the outcome is very unpredictable without TH or ROLE). If a data table has headers marked up using TD, then change these to TH. If a data table has no headers, add TH elements describing each row and/or column. If the table is only used for layout add role='presentation' to the TABLE element.
  • JAWS Reading: Treats tables without TH and ROLE as layout tables if the table contains cells above or below certain pixel sizes. This measurement is affected by browser window size, browser font size, and the browser used.
  • NVDA Reading: Applies a 'layout table' heuristic to tables without TH and ROLE which varies depending on the browser used and on the window size in some circumstances.
  • VoiceOver Safari OSX 10.9 Reading: Uses a sophisticated heuristic on tables without TH and ROLE, which is similar (but not identical) to the heuristic used by NVDA with Firefox.
Line 271 WCAG 1.0 A 5.1 Section 508 1194.22 (g) WCAG 2.0 A F91
Options



The 'width' attribute on the 'table' element is obsolete. Use CSS instead.
Line 271 HTML5

Use relative rather than absolute units in HTML attributes.
Use percentages rather than pixels for sizing frames and tables. Low-vision users often use the "large fonts" mode of Windows, which makes each pixel larger than usual. This usually causes problems with pixel based layouts, which also perform badly on handheld and widescreen displays. Percentage values "stretch" according to screen size and work on a large range of display sizes.
Line 273 WCAG 1.0 AA 3.4

This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute

  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute

710 <span style="white-space: nowrap; display: inline-block;">


All radio button groups should be contained in a FIELDSET tag.
When JAWS reads a page in Forms Mode it skips all markup other than form fields, labels and legends. Generally each radio button label is the answer to a question (e.g. Yes/No, Male/Female), so FIELDSET and LEGEND tags are needed to say what the question is.
Line 711 WCAG 1.0 AA 12.3
Options



Make sure one radio button in a radio button group is always selected. If users can choose not to activate any of the radio button choices, provide a choice labeled 'None'.
Line 711 Usability.gov 13:23

711<input type="radio" name="gsform.responseMap['PNCQ_57_RD_RB_169'].gsAnswerId" id="saveGreensheet_gsform_responseMap_'PNCQ_57_RD_RB_169'__gsAnswerIdSEL_112" value="SEL_112" class="form-radio-input form-validate required-validate"/>


Radio buttons with very generic labels need to be enclosed in a FIELDSET with a LEGEND that explains the label. Label used: " Yes"
Legend text is announced along with the label text for radio buttons inside a fieldset, which makes it easier for a screen reader user to understand what the radio button does. For example: <legend> Fries with your burger: </legend> <label> Yes </label> <label> No </label>

This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 809 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



This form has fields without LABEL elements or TITLE attributes.
Screen readers use LABEL elements or TITLE attributes to describe form fields to non-sighted users. Without these, forms are very hard to use with a screen reader. Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.
Line 809 Section 508 1194.22 (n)

Options



This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 968 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



This form has fields without LABEL elements or TITLE attributes.
Screen readers use LABEL elements or TITLE attributes to describe form fields to non-sighted users. Without these, forms are very hard to use with a screen reader. Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.
Line 968 Section 508 1194.22 (n)

All radio button groups should be contained in a FIELDSET tag.
When JAWS reads a page in Forms Mode it skips all markup other than form fields, labels and legends. Generally each radio button label is the answer to a question (e.g. Yes/No, Male/Female), so FIELDSET and LEGEND tags are needed to say what the question is.

Line 1501 HTML5
Options



This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 1501 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



This form has fields without LABEL elements or TITLE attributes.
Screen readers use LABEL elements or TITLE attributes to describe form fields to non-sighted users. Without these, forms are very hard to use with a screen reader. Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.
Line 1501 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options

Make sure each INPUT field has an associated LABEL tag describing the field.

1778 <span style="white-space: nowrap; display: inline-block;">


All radio button groups should be contained in a FIELDSET tag.
When JAWS reads a page in Forms Mode it skips all markup other than form fields, labels and legends. Generally each radio button label is the answer to a question (e.g. Yes/No, Male/Female), so FIELDSET and LEGEND tags are needed to say what the question is.
Line 1779 WCAG 1.0 AA 12.3

Options



This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)

This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 2431 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)

Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.

This form control has no programmatically determined name.

  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control

2761


This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 2761 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



This form has fields without LABEL elements or TITLE attributes.
Screen readers use LABEL elements or TITLE attributes to describe form fields to non-sighted users. Without these, forms are very hard to use with a screen reader. Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.

LABEL elements should be attached to the controls they label.
Add a FOR attribute set to the ID of the associated control, or wrap the LABEL round the associated control.
Line 2929 WCAG 1.0 AA 12.4 WCAG 2.0 A 4.1.2
Options


<label>Comments</label>

2930


This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 2930 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



This form has fields without LABEL elements or TITLE attributes.
Screen readers use LABEL elements or TITLE attributes to describe form fields to non-sighted users. Without these, forms are very hard to use with a screen reader. Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.
Line 2930 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



Use LABEL tags for each data entry field to show what data is expected.
Make sure each INPUT field has an associated LABEL tag describing the field.

This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 3108 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



This form has fields without LABEL elements or TITLE attributes.
Screen readers use LABEL elements or TITLE attributes to describe form fields to non-sighted users. Without these, forms are very hard to use with a screen reader. Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.
Line 3108 Section 508 1194.22 (n)

Legend text is announced along with the label text for radio buttons inside a fieldset, which makes it easier for a screen reader user to understand what the radio button does. For example: <legend> Fries with your burger: </legend> <label> Yes </label> <label> No </label>

3318


This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 3318 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



This form has fields without LABEL elements or TITLE attributes.
Screen readers use LABEL elements or TITLE attributes to describe form fields to non-sighted users. Without these, forms are very hard to use with a screen reader. Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.
Line 3318 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



Use LABEL tags for each data entry field to show what data is expected.
Make sure each INPUT field has an associated LABEL tag describing the field.

All radio button groups should be contained in a FIELDSET tag.
When JAWS reads a page in Forms Mode it skips all markup other than form fields, labels and legends. Generally each radio button label is the answer to a question (e.g. Yes/No, Male/Female), so FIELDSET and LEGEND tags are needed to say what the question is.

3471


This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 3471 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



This form has fields without LABEL elements or TITLE attributes.
Screen readers use LABEL elements or TITLE attributes to describe form fields to non-sighted users. Without these, forms are very hard to use with a screen reader. Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.
Line 3471 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



Use LABEL tags for each data entry field to show what data is expected.
Make sure each INPUT field has an associated LABEL tag describing the field.

3682


This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 3682 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



This form has fields without LABEL elements or TITLE attributes.
Screen readers use LABEL elements or TITLE attributes to describe form fields to non-sighted users. Without these, forms are very hard to use with a screen reader. Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.
Line 3682 Section 508 1194.22 (n)

This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)

All radio button groups should be contained in a FIELDSET tag.

When JAWS reads a page in Forms Mode it skips all markup other than form fields, labels and legends. Generally each radio button label is the answer to a question (e.g. Yes/No, Male/Female), so FIELDSET and LEGEND tags are needed to say what the question is.

4055


This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 4055 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



This form has fields without LABEL elements or TITLE attributes.
Screen readers use LABEL elements or TITLE attributes to describe form fields to non-sighted users. Without these, forms are very hard to use with a screen reader. Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.
Line 4055 Section 508 1194.22 (n)

<label>Comments</label>

4208


This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 4208 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



This form has fields without LABEL elements or TITLE attributes.
Screen readers use LABEL elements or TITLE attributes to describe form fields to non-sighted users. Without these, forms are very hard to use with a screen reader. Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.
Line 4208 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



Use LABEL tags for each data entry field to show what data is expected.
Make sure each INPUT field has an associated LABEL tag describing the field.

4379


This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 4379 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)

<label>Comments</label>

4604


This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 4604 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



This form has fields without LABEL elements or TITLE attributes.
Screen readers use LABEL elements or TITLE attributes to describe form fields to non-sighted users. Without these, forms are very hard to use with a screen reader. Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.
Line 4604 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



Use LABEL tags for each data entry field to show what data is expected.
Make sure each INPUT field has an associated LABEL tag describing the field.

4664 <span style="white-space: nowrap; display: inline-block;">


All radio button groups should be contained in a FIELDSET tag.
When JAWS reads a page in Forms Mode it skips all markup other than form fields, labels and legends. Generally each radio button label is the answer to a question (e.g. Yes/No, Male/Female), so FIELDSET and LEGEND tags are needed to say what the question is.
Line 4665 WCAG 1.0 AA 12.3

Radio buttons with very generic labels need to be enclosed in a FIELDSET with a LEGEND that explains the label. Label used: " Yes"

4821


This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 4821 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



This form has fields without LABEL elements or TITLE attributes.
Screen readers use LABEL elements or TITLE attributes to describe form fields to non-sighted users. Without these, forms are very hard to use with a screen reader. Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.

5142


This form control has no programmatically determined name.

A programmatically determined name allows screen readers to tell the user what the control does. To add a name do one of the following:

  • Use a LABEL element with the FOR attribute set to the ID of the form control
  • Wrap a LABEL element around the form control
  • Add a TITLE attribute
  • Add an ARIA-LABELLEDBY attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
  • Add an ARIA-LABEL attribute (not supported in all screen readers)
Line 5142 WCAG 2.0 A F68 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



This form has fields without LABEL elements or TITLE attributes.
Screen readers use LABEL elements or TITLE attributes to describe form fields to non-sighted users. Without these, forms are very hard to use with a screen reader. Forms designed to be completed online shall allow people using assistive technology to access the information, field elements, and functionality required for completion and submission of the form, including all directions and cues.
Line 5142 Section 508 1194.22 (n)
Options



Use LABEL tags for each data entry field to show what data is expected.
Make sure each INPUT field has an associated LABEL tag describing the field.

All radio button groups should be contained in a FIELDSET tag.

5497


Identify row and column headers in data tables using TH elements, and mark layout tables with role='presentation'.
Data tables allow screen reader users to understand column and row relationships. Layout tables read cells as a series of unrelated paragraphs with no tabular structure. Without TH or ROLE, screen readers apply heuristics to decide whether a table is a layout table or data table. These heuristics vary greatly between screen readers, and are affected by browser being used, window size, and font size (so the outcome is very unpredictable without TH or ROLE). If a data table has headers marked up using TD, then change these to TH. If a data table has no headers, add TH elements describing each row and/or column. If the table is only used for layout add role='presentation' to the TABLE element.
  • JAWS Reading: Treats tables without TH and ROLE as layout tables if the table contains cells above or below certain pixel sizes. This measurement is affected by browser window size, browser font size, and the browser used.
  • NVDA Reading: Applies a 'layout table' heuristic to tables without TH and ROLE which varies depending on the browser used and on the window size in some circumstances.
  • VoiceOver Safari OSX 10.9 Reading: Uses a sophisticated heuristic on tables without TH and ROLE, which is similar (but not identical) to the heuristic used by NVDA with Firefox.
Line 5497 WCAG 1.0 A 5.1 Section 508 1194.22 (g) WCAG 2.0 A F91
Options
